{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ca621b9b-05b6-4dcc-ae90-473562403459","content":"In modern MSTest (3.8+), you can inject `TestContext` via the constructor and combine it with `IAsyncInitialization` for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Sync setup here (e.g., configure options, create objects)\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void MyTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x+ injects `TestContext` automatically into the constructor (no `[TestInitialize]` needed for access).\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — Implement this interface for async setup that runs before each test.\n- The constructor handles sync work; `InitializeAsync()` handles anything requiring `await`.\n- This replaces the older pattern of a settable `TestContext` property + `[TestInitialize]` methods.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"36726936-1c80-4eba-bf11-d4f051f8a89f","outputTokens":324,"requestId":"EBE2:334824:7AFD75:82CC8D:6A044E85"},"id":"5c1ad658-7225-4a7f-bd9f-2fc392364799","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:12:32.465Z","parentId":"6c343a21-0c8d-4be2-9ded-6ca1f3e7c87e"}
